 “Our exit from Alaska does not in any way diminish BP's commitment to America,” Dudley said. "We remain very bullish on the US energy sector. In just the last three years we have invested more than $20 billion in the US and we will continue to look at further investment opportunities here." BP employs about 1,600 people in association with its Alaska business. BP said it is “committed to providing clarity about their future as soon as possible as part of the transition process with Hilcorp.” Hilcorp has been operating in Alaska since 2012 and is the state’s largest private oil and gas operator. Hilcorp had purchased interests from BP in four Alaska North Slope oil fields in 2014.  The deal is subject to state and federal regulatory approval. View the discussion thread. The Hill 1625 K Street, NW Suite 900 Washington DC 20006 | 202-628-8500 tel | 202-628-8503 fax The contents of this site are ©2019 Capitol Hill Publishing Corp., a subsidiary of News Communications, Inc.
